What’s your goal at an even higher level than that I mean? The reason I ask is that, if your goal is to precisely reach a certain point to do a multi-element auto, you’re going to struggle a lot because % output is very low precision. Depending on how much time you have I would recommend doing 1 of the following:

  1. Research closed-loop control. This can be a large undertaking, especially for smaller teams. But will let you tell motors to drive a specific distance precisely, allowing you to do larger autos. This is a pretty large undertaking, especially this late in the season though.

  2. Try and score your preload and balance. This is what I would really recommend you do. This will make your auto more competitive than many teams at your event, and it’s doable with % output, and in general, doesn’t require majorly changing the way you control your drivetrain.

Looking at the code, it seems like you update the Drive values and then go into loops that are waiting for specific conditions.

Not sure if this is the issue you’re running into, but at least for you to be aware: The drive functions include a Safety Configuration that stops the drivetrain if it doesn’t receive a value in 100ms or so. It is possible you are hitting this condition and, thus, seeing your robot stop and not perform the commands as expected.

I recommend moving the Drive functions into your loop and adding a Wait (ms) function of some 20 to 50 ms to ensure a) that you keep updating the drive train values (even if it’s with the same output over and over) and 2) that you don’t overload the CPU with a function in a while loop that is checking for a condition faster than needed.

See more information on this here:

  • [FRC 2017] Autonomous Timed Movement Tutorial
  • Safety Configuration Tutorial - LabVIEW for FRC

Cheers,
Oscar
